b"I think sometimes people feel this pressure to be happy all the time. However, people aren't happy all the time throughout the holidays. If there are things that you think about that make you sad, I guess I would say first, don't be alarmed that you feel sad."
b"And I know Frank misses both his mother and father. I miss my mother and father. They've all passed on. We miss the people that we can't be with. I would call it a bittersweet time always."

b"I know that there are a lot of people who get stressed at the holidays because they feel as though they're not supposed to feel sad. But we all do feel sad sometimes at the holidays. Frank and I miss our daughter, especially at the holidays."

b"The #holidays are a happy time.  They're a very busy time, too. I love the cooking part. I love the buying presents part. I love the setting the table part. I love most of all being with everyone. But holidays can also be a bittersweet time."
b'Reflecting back on our conversation, I wanted to share some advice that I think we could all use as we head into the #holidays and confront what is sometimes a not so happy holiday.'

b'As citizens it is both our responsibility and our right to hold elected officials accountable: for their words, their actions and the consequences of both.'

b'Every elected official, including the President, is there to serve the citizenry, not the other way around. It is not a citizen\xe2\x80\x99s job to \xe2\x80\x9cbe loyal\xe2\x80\x9d; it is the official\xe2\x80\x99s job to earn our loyalty. And when they cannot, we vote them out of office.'
b'We abdicate our responsibility to help create a \xe2\x80\x9cmore perfect union.\xe2\x80\x9d  And in this country, the citizen, not the President, is sovereign.'

b'It is not a citizen\xe2\x80\x99s role to be a \xe2\x80\x9cloyal fan\xe2\x80\x9d of one side or the other. We have no obligation to follow party orthodoxy, whatever it is. When we silence our voices, we relinquish our power as citizen leaders to shape the nation.'
b'I am not alone. Many others have been intimidated into silence or compelled to defend the indefensible.'

b'When did so many Republicans decide that we should also pledge allegiance to The Party and swear fidelity to President Trump? I have been called \xe2\x80\x9cdisloyal\xe2\x80\x9d because I am critical of Trump.'
b'When we swear to \xe2\x80\x9cprotect and defend\xe2\x80\x9d the Constitution, we promise to uphold the rights, the laws and the institutions that define and govern our nation.'
b'When we pledge allegiance, we reaffirm our citizenship in a nation founded on ideas and ideals - not ethnicity, race, religion or origin.'
b'Our Constitution is the document that protects those liberties and delivers that justice.'

b'In this country, we pledge allegiance to the flag, not the president. We swear fidelity to the Constitution, not the party.  Our flag is a symbol of \xe2\x80\x9cone nation... indivisible... with liberty and justice for all.\xe2\x80\x9d (1/10)'

b'What is inarguable however, is that words and behavior - in short, character - count.  Character can lift us up or tear us down. Tone is always set at the top.'

b'Our culture has become angrier, ruder, cruder, louder, less tolerant and more violent. People are more afraid, less hopeful, more tribal. Is it fair to place all this at the feet of the President? Of course not; nothing is that simple.'

b'When a President routinely condemns, ridicules and denigrates others; uses language that is offensive and racist; foments resentment, fear and grievance for political purposes; then there are real consequences.'

b'As the President, Mr. Trump sets the tone. There are other politicians whose tone and language are also destructive. But there is only one President. And so we must hold every President to a higher standard. Such is the price and the responsibility of the Office.'

b'Behavior, language, and tone are all about \xe2\x80\x9chow things get done\xe2\x80\x9d.  They define character.  Character is revealed over time in the pattern of behavior, language and tone.  And character is destiny, for a person and for a nation.'
b'Over decades I have developed leaders of all kinds in all kinds of places through both my business and charitable work, so I know how things get done is always as important as what gets done.'
b'In the midst of all these important conversations, let us pause and reflect on the one thing we all know to be true: character counts and tone is set at the top.'

b'In the wake of three more mass shootings in a single week, there will be many debates on the role of guns and the importance of gun control; on the rise of domestic terrorism and white supremacy; on the internet as a breeding ground for grievance, resentment and violence.'
b'We\xe2\x80\x99re excited to share this conversation with you and more when we launch Season 2 of my podcast By Example this fall.'
